</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="323" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="323">
The original description stated that 
<taxonomicName family="Scelionidae" genus="G." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="G. eremiogryon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" rank="species" species="eremiogryon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">G. eremiogryon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has bidentate mandibles and the subsequent discussion expressed 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mineoâ€™s">Mineo's</normalizedToken>
idea that 
<taxonomicName family="Scelionidae" genus="G." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="G. eremiogryon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" rank="species" species="eremiogryon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">G. eremiogryon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was intermediate between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Gryon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gryon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Gryon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1951" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Eremioscelio" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eremioscelio" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Eremioscelio</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Given that the latter is now treated as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Gryon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gryon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Gryon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we are fairly confident that this species belongs in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1833" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Gryon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Gryon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="323" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="323">Gryon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
